title: Urge Your TX Rep to Protect Voting Rights: VOTE NO on HB 5337/SB 16
description:
The Texas Legislature needs to hear from you! Contact your Texas House Representative urging them to VOTE NO! 

HB 5337/SB 16 would create unnecessary barriers for Texans trying to register to vote by requiring proof of citizenship, such as a passport or birth certificate. This bill adds extra hurdles to an already burdensome process, even though the state would still be responsible for verifying citizenship through its own systems. In the end, it makes voter registration harder without solving any real problems.

HB 5337/SB 16 will do more harm than good, disproportionately impacting eligible voters, especially young people, seniors, and naturalized citizens, who might not have these documents readily available and whose status is likely more difficult to verify. 

The bottom line is that our elections are already secure, but what they aren’t is fully accessible. We should be working to build a democracy where every voice is heard, not one where more are shut out.


Note: Once you hit "Contact My Rep" you'll be directed to the Texas House of Representatives member page and a sample script will be sent via email. To find your rep, use the link below to input your address. After you know who your Texas House Representative is, return to the landing page and click on your members profile. title: East Kentucky Community Remembrance Project Service Day 2025
description:
On Saturday, May 24th, the East Kentucky Community Remembrance Project and the Big Sandy Chapter of Kentuckians For The Commonwealth are organizing a free community lunch and service project in Wayland, Kentucky.

We will gather at 9:30am in Wayland to get organized for the morning service project clearing brush from a nearby cemetery where many Black residents, including some who were enslaved people, are buried. We'll leave most cars at the Wayland Community Center and shuttle in a few vehicles to the nearby cemetery.

There will be a rideshare and caravan departing Prestonsburg at 8:30am from the parking lot behind the Town Center shops at 152 N Lake Dr, Prestonsburg, KY 41653. If anyone would like a ride, or to follow a driver who knows their way to Wayland, please reach out to Eric Fields at eric@kftc.org.

We hope this service project is a step on a path towards racial understanding, healing, justice, and transformation. Because of previous service projects, we expect to mostly be clearing weeds and very young trees and brush.

We need volunteers, but we also recognize that clearing trees and brush isn't a good fit for all folks. All are welcome to enjoy lunch and fellowship from 12:30pm - 3:00pm at Wayland Community Center, whether or not you also sign up for the morning work crew. There will be a donation jar to help cover the costs of lunch, but lunch is free and everyone is welcome.

We'll use this time to learn and reflect on the history of the local community, including the heritage of many local Black families, some of whom remain and many who have moved away from the area. We will discuss a specific incident of racial violence, the lynching of a Black man named Fred Shannon, that took place at the Wayland jail in October of 1924. We will also hold a ceremony in which we place a historical marker at the old Wayland jail, the site of Shannon's killing. The historical marker has been provided to the EKY Community Remembrance Project by the Equal Justice Initiative. You can learn more about the work they do [HERE](https://eji.org/).

Please RSVP if you plan to join us on May 24th and let us know what parts of the day you will attend.

If more than one member of your household plans to attend, please register each person separately to help us estimate how much food to prepare. Thank you.

People of all ages are welcome for lunch. Working volunteers must be 16 years or older.

It is important to protect everyone's health and safety during this event. We will provide sun screen, water, and a first aid kit. We ask everyone to bring their own water bottle, work gloves, and sturdy shoes. If you do not have the necessary safety items, let us know and we'll follow up with you to make a plan.

The Wayland Community Center is located at 2662 King Kelly Coleman Hwy, Wayland, KY 41666. It will be on the right on Rte. 7, 3.9 miles after turning off of Rte. 80
accessibility_notes: The cleanup site is not accessible to all people due to uneven ground, low brush, and a slope. The lunch site has a ramp to the porch and first floor restrooms, but the door to the building is not automatic.

description:
Join us for a virtual comment party to speak out against the proposed hybrid gas-electric compressor station in Chesapeake, VA. This facility — planned near several environmental justice communities and a local middle school — would be tied to the Virginia Reliability Project and used to power AI paper production for Smurfit WestRock.

Compressor stations are industrial facilities that release toxic air pollutants while pushing gas through pipelines, thereby placing surrounding communities at risk of long-term health and environmental harm.

We need at least 25 public comments submitted to the Virginia State Corporation Commission (SCC) by May 23rd to trigger a formal hearing and your voice can help us reach that goal.

At this event, we’ll give you a brief overview of the project, walk you through the comment process, provide talking points, and answer any questions you have. Whether it’s your first time taking action or you’ve done this before, you’ll leave with a comment submitted and a sense of connection to others fighting for environmental justice in Virginia.

title: Pride, Poetry, & Plastics Workshop with Storytelling with Saris
description:
We're excited to join Storytelling with Saris for the launch of World Pride in DC with a workshop focused on the disproportionate impacts of climate change and sea level rise on the LGBTQ+ community. Join us for an evening of art, pride, poetry writing, plastics education, and a light dinner.  

This year's theme is the Fabric of Freedom, and saris are a particularly sustainable garment, traditionally made of cotton or silk, passed down from generation to generation within families. Unfortunately, many types of clothing today are now made from plastic-based products and petrochemicals like polyester, creating a cycle of fast fashion. These materials are derived from fossil fuels and are bad for our health and warm the climate. 

This workshop will empower each of us to use art as a form of advocacy as we write poetry and make art on the saris inspired by the courage and rich history of the LGBTQ+ community who are disproportionately impacted by climate change.
